### useNavigate

`useNavigate` returns a function for programmatic navigation. Use it to redirect users after form submissions, logins, or timeouts.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

const navigate = useNavigate();
```

### Basic Navigation

```jsx
function LoginPage() {
  const navigate = useNavigate();

  const handleLogin = async (formData) => {
    await login(formData);
    navigate('/dashboard');
  };

  return <LoginForm onSubmit={handleLogin} />;
}
```

### Navigation Options

```jsx
// Navigate to path
navigate('/dashboard');

// Replace current entry (no back button)
navigate('/login', { replace: true });

// Pass state to target route
navigate('/profile', { state: { userId: 123 } });

// Go back / forward
navigate(-1);  // Go back
navigate(1);   // Go forward

// Relative navigation
navigate('settings');   // Relative to current route
navigate('../admin');   // Up one level
```

### Navigate Component

For declarative navigation (e.g., in redirects):

```jsx
import { Navigate } from 'react-router-dom';

function ProtectedRoute({ user, children }) {
  if (!user) {
    return <Navigate to="/login" replace />;
  }
  return children;
}
```

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `navigate(to)` | Navigate forward |
| `navigate(to, { replace: true })` | Replace history entry |
| `navigate(delta)` | Go back/forward by delta |
| `Navigate` component | Declarative redirect |

> **Key Point:** useNavigate replaces the old `useHistory` hook from React Router v5. Use `navigate(-1)` for back buttons. The `replace` option prevents users from navigating back to login after authenticating.

codeExample:
import { useNavigate } from 'react-router-dom';

function OrderConfirmation({ orderId }) {
  const navigate = useNavigate();

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Order #{orderId} confirmed</h1>
      <button onClick={() => navigate('/orders')}>View Orders</button>
      <button onClick={() => navigate('/')}>Back to Home</button>
    </div>
  );
}
